SIMPLE: eyelet
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Eyelet
<hw>Eye"let`</hw> <pr>(⟦imac⟧"l⟦ecr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>⟦oe⟧illet</ets>, dim. of <ets>⟦oe⟧il</ets> eye, fr. L.
<ets>oculus</ets>. See <er>Eye</er>, and cf. <er>Oillet</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A small hole or perforation to receive a cord or
fastener, as in garments, sails, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A metal ring or grommet, or short metallic tube, the
ends of which can be bent outward and over to fasten it in place; --
used to line an eyelet hole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Eyelet hole</b></col>, <cd>a hole made for an
eyelet.</cd> -- <col><b>Eyelet punch</b></col>, <cd>a machine for
punching eyelet holes and fastening eyelets, as in paper or cloth.</cd>
-- <col><b>Eyelet ring</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Eyelet</er>,
2.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Eyeleteer</ent>⟦br⟧
